article.description: Betty Lennox scored 23 of her season-high 29 points in the second half as the host Seattle Storm rallied to end the Connecticut Sun's eight-game winning streak with a 95-86 victory Wednesday night.
article.headline: Lennox scores 23 of her 29 in the second half
article.linkText: Lennox, Storm rally to snap Sun's 8-game run
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Betty Lennox finally broke out Wednesday night,
and it looked very much like last October's WNBA Finals.

Lennox scored 23 of her season-high 29 points in the second half
as the Seattle Storm rallied to end the Connecticut Sun's
eight-game winning streak with a 95-86 victory.

Lennox was the MVP of last year's finals after averaging 22.3
points as Seattle beat Connecticut in three games.

"She's kind of been missing in action for a little while. That
second half, that's Betty when she's just aggressive and
attacking," said Seattle coach Anne Donovan. "Reminiscent of
October of last year, don't you think?"

Connecticut lost for the first time since dropping its season
opener to Detroit 78-67. Mike Thibault coached the Sun despite the
death of his mother Wednesday morning, and did not inform the team
about the passing until after the game.

Thibault did not speak to the media.

"He knew before the game," Sun assistant Bernadette Mattox
said. "It's hard."

Seattle, which set a new franchise record for points in a game,
took its first lead at 81-80 on a pair of free throws from Sue Bird
with 4:32 left. Taj McWilliams-Franklin responded at the other end,
but Janell Burse's putback with 3:45 left gave the Storm an 83-82
lead they would not relinquish.

Lennox added two free throws, then Iziane Castro Marques hit a
3-pointer with 1:35 left and added a runner with a minute remaining
to put Seattle ahead by five.

Lennox had not scored in double-figures in Seattle's previous
two games.

"I was playing pretty much under control, not as aggressive in
the first half," said Lennox whose 12 field goals made are the
most in the league this season. "When I get into a mode where they
get physical back with me, that's what makes me have my best games.

Connecticut scored just seven points in the final 5:30, as
Seattle closed the game on a 15-5 run.

Lauren Jackson added 23 points and a season-high 17 rebounds for
Seattle. Castro Marques finished with 15 points and reserve Suzy
Batkovic added 13.

McWilliams-Franklin led the Sun with 21 points and was one of
five players in double figures. Lindsay Whalen and Asjha Jones had
16 apiece, Nykesha Sales added 12 and Katie Douglas 11.

"You don't like to give up 50 points in a half, but overall I
think we were in the game the whole way," Whalen said. "In the
end, they made a few shots ... and got us out of it a little bit."

Bird played in her first game since June 7, when she broke her
nose and right orbital bone against the Sun. Bird made her first
shot, 46 seconds into the game, but missed her next six shots and
finished with just 3 points.

Still, Bird's presence helped as Seattle committed only eight
turnovers and allowed Lennox to focus on her scoring.

"I pretty much ran every play at the end to get (Lennox) the
ball," Bird said.

Bird was injured when Jackson accidentally elbowed her late in
Seattle's 81-69 loss to Connecticut. The Storm went 2-2 without
Bird.

It was the second meeting this season between the teams, but the
first game in Seattle since the Storm beat the Sun 74-60 in Game 3
of last year's WNBA Finals.

Much as they have during their winning streak, the Sun jumped
out early and made the opponent rally. Entering Wednesday's game,
the Sun had trailed only once in the last four games -- 6-4 against
Los Angeles on Monday.

That remained much the same against Seattle. Connecticut shot
more than 60 percent for much of the first half, and built a
10-point lead.

The Storm stayed close, trailing 49-44 at halftime, and tied the
game at 61 on a basket from Jackson.
